   <abstract>Using the Antarctic expeditions of Richard E. Byrd as a frame of reference, this dissertation places Antarctica in a more central role in our understanding of the United States in the mid-twentieth century. Scholarship on American imperialism frequently neglects the nation's relationship with Antarctica, since the US never formally claimed territory on the continent, but Byrd's efforts to establish an American territory or settler colony in the region challenge these assumptions. From his headquarters at the pseudo-frontier town of Little America, and back in the US, Byrd created an American alternative to the European polar explorers of the "Heroic Age" whom he admired, rooted in Southern concepts of honor and masculinity. While Antarctica lacked indigenous human populations, it did not prove a tabula rasa on which Byrd could easily replicate American colonization scrubbed of its less-pleasant elements, and a study of the exploration writing produced by Byrd and his contemporaries reveals the unique ways in which US Antarctic history is written. Often credited as an early promoter of the internationalist system codified by the 1959 Antarctic Treaty System, close analysis of Byrd and his influences complicates that understanding.</abstract>
